<HEAD>Tornadoes Bear Down On South, Midwest</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to update with storms today in Texas,
Northwest, picking up at the 5th graf previous.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Violent thunderstorms lashed much of the South and Midwest today
with wind up to 85 mph after a day of stormy weather that included
several tornadoes and large hail.
   Thunderstorms that began Thursday night stretched this morning
from Texas to north-central Oklahoma, from southeast Arkansas to
Mississippi and from Louisiana into Florida, southeast Alabama and
eastern North Carolina.
   Near the southern tip of Texas, a squall line hit South Padre
Island with wind up to 85 mph about 6 a.m., overturning some
trailers, causing minor injuries and blowing roofs off some
buildings there and in Brownsville, the National Weather Service
said.
   Also at Brownsville, wind up to 62 mph overturned some small
airplanes at the airport, and power lines were downed at Skidmore,
the weather service said.
   In the six hours up to 7 a.m., 1.24 inches of rain fell at the
Navy air station at Corpus Christi, Texas, and 1.87 inches was
reported at Port Isabel.
   High wind also blew today in the Northwest, with gusts to 70 mph
on parts of the Oregon coast, as a new storm system approached.
Showers were scattered from northern Idaho to northern California.
   On Thursday, tornadoes touched down in Texas near Cottonwood and
Austin during the afternoon and evening while wind gusted to 70 mph
at Abilene.
   In Spring Lake, N.C., thunderstorm wind gusts blew over signs
and scattered debris across roads.
   Hail up to golf ball size pelted Zephyr and Kelleen, Texas, as
well as Newton Grove, N.C.
   Thursday's violent weather included four tornadoes, five storms
with possible tornadoes, 63 reports of dime-size or larger hail and
19 reports of wind damage or winds of more than 60 mph. While many
of the reports came from Oklahoma and Texas, the list included
North Carolina, Arkansas Mississippi, Alabama, Kansas and Virginia.
There were no reports of injury or major damage.
   Today's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms
from the southern Plains to the lower Missisippi Valley, the
Tennessee Valley, northern sections of the central Gulf Coast
states and Georgia, and the Carolinas; and scattered rain from the
central Appalachians to the upper Ohio Valley and the lower Great
Lakes, and from northern California to the Pacific Northwest.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 70s and 80s across much
of the nation; in the 60s from northern Wisconsin to the Ohio
Valley and the mid- Atlantic states; in the 50s from much of New
England into southern New York and northern Pennsylvania; into the
90s from the central Gulf Coast to northern Florida, from the
Southern California valleys and southern Nevada into the Rio Grande
Valley; and between 100 and 110 degrees across the desert Southwest.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 32
degrees at Houlton, Maine, to 89 degrees at Blythe, Calif., and
Phoenix, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 70 fair; Boston 51 cloudy; Buffalo 50 cloudy;
Charleston, S.C. 73 hazy; Cincinnati 57 cloudy; Cleveland 54 fair;
Detroit 51 partly cloudy; Miami 78 fair; New York 52 fair;
Philadelphia 52 partly cloudy; Pittsburgh 54 cloudy; Portland,
Maine 42 fair; Washington 55 cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 68 fair; Chicago 53 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
67 partly cloudy; Denver 59 partly cloudy; Des Moines 70 cloudy;
Indianapolis 58 cloudy; Kansas City 61 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul
62 cloudy; Nashville 71 hazy; New Orleans 72 fair; St. Louis 72
cloudy.
   _West: Albuquerque 70 windy; Anchorage 47 fair; Las Vegas 79
fair; Los Angeles 64 fair; Phoenix 89 fair; Salt Lake City 59 fair;
San Diego 63 fair; San Francisco 60 fair; Seattle 49 cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 52 cloudy; Toronto 48 showery.
  
